These were not the only letters prepared for this flight. A
larger number had been aboard the other plane, the PN-9, No. 3. But
Snody and his covers were forced down about 300 miles off the California
coast. Rodgers, too, had more than two covers.
While in California preparing for the flight, Rodgers, who
had formerly commanded the Ford Island Air Station near Honolulu, met
a friend from the Islands,
She asked him to
take a few letters to her friends in Hawa11. Possibly this was suggested
by Rodgers. These covers also flew - and sailed - with Rodgers although
the existence of these other letters on the Rodgers flight was never
Included in the Navy's official report. One of these lost John Rodgers'
covers is illustrated.
